<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1436,291,894]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,760,786]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Remarks.</emphasis>
This species first branched off in the 
<taxonomicName box="[743,818,760,786]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Phortica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="glabra">
<emphasis box="[743,818,760,786]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">glabra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subgroup (
<figureCitation box="[946,1012,760,786]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1683,1708]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,779,1658]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,777,1658]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 1. The strict consensus tree resulting from the parsimony analysis I (PAUP* v4.0a166) of the data matrix of 40 spp. × 66 morphological characters (Appendix 1) for the genus Phortica (especially focusing on the subgenus Ashima). Synapomorphies (solid circle: nonhomoplastic; open circle: homoplastic) inferred from both ACCTRAN and DELTRAN character optimization are indicated on each internal branch along with support values (bootstrap frequency %)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3884614" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3884614/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). The remaining three species form a cluster (BP = 96%) with three synapomorphies (
<figureCitation box="[702,770,796,822]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1683,1708]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,779,1658]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,777,1658]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 1. The strict consensus tree resulting from the parsimony analysis I (PAUP* v4.0a166) of the data matrix of 40 spp. × 66 morphological characters (Appendix 1) for the genus Phortica (especially focusing on the subgenus Ashima). Synapomorphies (solid circle: nonhomoplastic; open circle: homoplastic) inferred from both ACCTRAN and DELTRAN character optimization are indicated on each internal branch along with support values (bootstrap frequency %)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3884614" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3884614/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
): pregonite (
<figureCitation box="[918,1007,796,822]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="32.[151,250,1936,1961]" captionTargetBox="[166,1420,633,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[166,1420,633,1910]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 9. Phortica (Ashima) takehiroi Toda, sp. nov. (♂ paratype). A, Head (caudal view); B, antenna; C, palpus and prob- ocsis; D, prementum; E, abdominal sternites; F, periphallic organs (caudolateral view); G–I, phallic organs (lateral, ventrolateral and ventral views, respectively). Scale bars: 0.1 mm in B–D, F–I; 0.5 mm in A, E." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3884632" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3884632/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 9G</figureCitation>
) nearly entirely sclerotized (ch.43-1), only angulated in ventrosubapical portion of apical knob (ch.46-1), and coarsely serrated on ventrodistal portion (ch.50-1).
</paragraph>
